name: Meadow Lane
description: The route to the ground is signposted 'Football and Cricket Traffic' from all directions.

name: Boundary Park
description: Roads in Oldham and the surrounding areas, including the local motorway network, will be busier than normal on match day. The main road that will be affected by congestion prior to kick-off will be the A571 Oldham Road between the hospital and Broadway. Fans can take the tram from Manchester Victoria or use a Park & Ride site. Train services run into Manchester Piccadilly, Oxford Road and Victoria. Walking and cycling are good options to get to and from the match.

name: Roots Hall
description: The MidexPRO East Stand is the main stand at Roots Hall with 2,878 seats and Executive Boxes, the Gilbert & Rose Stand can seat up to 3,337, the Solopress North Bank can hold up to 2,248 fans, the Jonathan Rhys Recruitment South Stand is a two-tier stand with 935 seats, and the Family Stand is the lower tier of the South Stand and blocks Q&R in the West Stand and can hold 2,029 fans.

name: Gateshead International Stadium
description: Gateshead FC have played at the International Stadium since moving from Redheugh Park during the 1971/72 season. An all-seated venue, the International Stadium boasts a capacity of 11,800.

name: Racecourse Ground
description: The Racecourse Ground has four stands, all of which are all-seater and fully covered. Refreshments and a club shop are available. The nearest train station is Wrexham General, and the nearest bus station is Wrexham bus station.

name: The Shay
description: It consists of the South Stand (a terraced stand behind the goal for home fans), the Skircoat Stand (all seater down the Skircoat Road side of the Shay Stadium and when open is for away supporters), and the East Stand (which holds 4000 fans and provides banqueting suites, bars, food areas and hospitality boxes). The South Stand Bar is located under the stand at the Spring Hall end and is open to all fans.

name: Huish Park
description: The Family Stand at Huish Park (Block G) is situated at the home end of the main Tamburino Stand. Away supporters are housed in the open away end of the ground which is a standing area only. There is also the provision of a seated area (Block P & PP) in the away end of the Screwfix Stand. Snack bars, toilets, matchday programmes, and a club shop are all available at the stadium. There are several pubs around Huish Park the nearest being the Airfield Tavern and the Arrow.

name: Glanford Park
description: Glanford Park is one of the most accessible stadiums in the EFL, located just off the M181. There is free parking for blue badge holders, as well as a 600-space car park at the ground available for £5. Bus and train services are also available, with the station situated two miles away from the stadium.

name: The Walks Stadium
description: The stadium is located on Tennyson Road and is 5 minutes away from the train station. Limited parking is available at the stadium and matchday programmes can be purchased from the ticket office, online shop, or from sellers on matchdays.

name: York Community Stadium
description: This community stadium leisure complex heralded a new era for sports and  community services in the city. It provided a new football and rugby  stadium for professional and community sport as well as leisure facilities  for York.

name: Moss Lane
description: The official ground capacity is 6,085 and consists of a Hale End terrace, Golf Road terrace, Popular Side terrace, Main Stand, and Family Stand. Food and drink are available at the Community Sports Hall bar, permanent catering facility at the Golf Road End, and the mobile canteen at the away end. The J. Davidson Stadium can be reached by car or coach, public transport, or walking from the town centre.

name: Recreation Ground
alternateName: The EBB Stadium at the Recreation Ground

sponsor.name: The EBB Stadium at the Recreation Ground

description: Aldershot Town FC's EBB Stadium is located in Aldershot, Hampshire, and is easily accessed by road, train and bus. Parking is available in the town centre multi-storey car park on Wellington Avenue, and the EBB Stadium is a five-minute walk from Aldershot Train Station. There are a number of pubs and restaurants in the area, as well as cashpoints at Santander and the Esso petrol station.

name: Cherrywood Road
description: Over the last few years the Easy As HGV Stadium has undergone - and is undergoing - a major transformation. The tired old stands have either gone or been completely refurbished.

name: Bower Fold
description: Leave the M6, M1, M62 or M60 at Junction 19, 35a, 18 or 24 respectively and follow the A556, A616, A628, and M67 to Junction 4. Turn left onto the A57 then left onto B6174. Turn left onto Roe Cross Road and follow for 1 3/4 miles. Bower Fold is on the left opposite a sharp right turn next to the art gallery. Parking can be found on the streets on the right of Mottram Road.

name: Spencer Stadium
alternateName: The Banbury Plant Hire Community Stadium

sponsor.name: The Banbury Plant Hire Community Stadium

description: The restricted access to the ground can lead to long delays in and around the station when leaving after matches, especially on Saturdays. Town centre car parks are up to 15 minutes walk from the ground.

name: New Bucks Head
description: New Bucks Head Stadium is a Football League 'A' graded stadium and is considered one of the best non-league grounds in the country. The stadium has a capacity of 5500 and was built in 2000-2003 to replace the Bucks Head ground. It has a disabled entrance and two disabled toilets. The stadium also has a Learning Centre which houses club offices, a bar, meeting and education rooms.

name: Aggborough
description: Away fans at Aggborough will typically be seated in the East Stand or South Stand terrace. Parking is very limited and is restricted to the South Stand at a cost of £5.

name: Plainmoor
description: Plainmoor Stadium is situated in St. Marychurch, an area of Torquay within walking distance of the town centre. There is plenty to do in Torbay, with the English Riviera offering beaches, attractions, history, and places to eat and drink.

name: Victoria Road
description: Victoria Road has been a football ground since 1917, and has seen many improvements over the years. It has hosted a number of important matches, including a Women's Full international match, UEFA Youth International matches, various County and League Cup finals, and an FAXI match. The floodlights were replaced in 2012, and the SD Samuels Stand was opened in 2009.

name: Kingfield Stadium
description: The Laithwaite Community Stadium is located on the A247 opposite the entrance to Woking Park. It can easily be reached by car, leaving the M25 at either junctions 10 or 11 and following the signs towards Woking. There is no parking around the stadium, so it is recommended to use Heathside car park. It can also be reached by train, with a journey time of 28 minutes from Waterloo. Once at Woking Station, you can either follow the signposted route down White Rose Lane or take the more direct route by turning right down the station approach road. Follow either of these routes until you reach the entrance to Woking Park, then follow the path through until you reach the main road directly opposite the ground.

name: Haig Avenue
description: The nearest railway station is Meols Cop on the Manchester to Southport line which is a ten minute walk from the ground.

name: Mill Farm
description: Mill Farm includes a state-of-the-art football stadium, 3G football and hockey pitches, a sports bar with 20 TVs, restaurant and café, conference & event facilities, and Aldi supermarket, Euro Garages petrol station, Spar, Greggs bakery and KFC fast food restaurant. It's easily accessible by car via the M55 and public transport via the 61 bus or Kirkham and Wesham Railway Station.

name: Deva Stadium
description: Located outside the city centre in the Sealand Road Industrial Estate, the  stadium is notable for straddling the England-Wales border. The pitch  itself is in Wales (Flintshire), with the front gates and main office  in England.

name: Clarence Park
description: Clarence Park has always enjoyed a reputation for having one of the finest playing surfaces in non-league football, even the early match reports praise the high quality of St Albans home pitch to the detriment of other grounds. Down the years a large number of clubs heading for Wembley to play in the FA Cup final have stopped off at Clarence Park the day before the final for a spot of training.

name: War Memorial Sports Ground
description: Carshalton British Rail Station is five minutes walk from the ground.

name: Jakemans Community Stadium
description: Matchday car parking at the Jakemans Community Stadium is exclusively for  car park season pass holders and club guests in season 2022-2023. Further  car parking spaces will become available following the completion of  construction works at the Community Stadium in the future.

name: Hayes Lane
description: Hayes Lane is a non-segregated stadium. Directions to the stadium include taking the M25 motorway and following the A21 and A232 roads. On Saturdays, the Broomfields bar and kitchen opens at 8am and the Jim Brown Club Shop opens at 9am. Turnstiles open at 1:30 pm and team news is announced an hour before kick-off. Half-time entertainment is available and food/drink can be purchased from the concessions.

memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Woodside Park
alternateName: R & D Advisors UK Ltd Stadium

sponsor.name: R & D Advisors UK Ltd Stadium

description: The grandstand is covered and all seated with the addition of press facilities and directors box.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Damson Park
description: Solihull Railway Station is two and half miles away, Birmingham International Station is one and half miles away, there is limited car parking available at the ground for £5, or a 40% discount when parking at the NCP Car Park at Birmingham Airport Cargo Term (B26 3QT). The X12 bus runs to the ground every 15/20 minutes and food huts, fan zone, and two main downstairs bars in the clubhouse building provide refreshments.

name: Meadow Park
description: All National League fixtures at Meadow Park will operate under full segregation, with visiting supporters in the South End and home supporters in the rest of the stadium. There is no supporter parking available, but there are public car parks nearby. There are disabled facilities available, and carers are admitted free of charge with proof of a valid carer's card or other proof of need.

name: Nyewood Lane
description: The ground is situated in Nyewood Lane, Bognor Regis - a short distance from both the seafront and the town centre and railway station.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Broadhurst Park
description: FC United's Broadhurst Park is the UK's first new ground to be built and funded by a supporter-owned football club. It has 4,400 capacity and the members were involved in the design and construction process. It is also the first pollinator-friendly football stadium in the UK, and the funding came from a Community Share Scheme, other fundraising, Sport England, the Football Foundation, Manchester City Council, Social Investment Business, Manchester College and Viridor.

name: The Northolme
alternateName: The Dave Longstaff Martin and Co Arena

sponsor.name: The Dave Longstaff Martin and Co Arena

description: Gainsborough Trinity Football Club changed the name of their home stadium to The Dave Longstaff Martin and Co Arena in honour of Dave Longstaff, who recently passed away. The name change is a fitting tribute to Dave and his family, and a way to thank them and Martin and Co, Gainsborough for their generosity and loyalty to the club.

name: Victory Park
alternateName: The Chorley Group Victory Park Stadium

sponsor.name: The Chorley Group Victory Park Stadium

description: Victory Park is named after the outcome of World War One, with work  beginning on the ground (an old ash tip) in 1919 and the Club moving in a  year later after buying the land for £868.

name: Ewen Fields
description: In 2014, Benfica visited Ewen Fields for a UEFA Youth League Quarter Final  fixture against Manchester City.

name: Cressing Road
description: The ground has a recently extended Main Seated Stand that can accommodate 553 spectators including six wheelchair spaces. The Clubhouse End of the ground has recently been upgraded with a new terrace. This end of the ground can accommodate 1,131 spectators.

name: Gallagher Stadium
description: The Gallagher Stadium is minutes away from the town centre, where you'll find more shops than there is at Bluewater. The ground is seconds away from the River Medway and the beautiful Whatman Park.

name: Tameside Stadium
description: The ground has two covered stands and is fully terraced on all four sides  and currently holds the FA 'B' Grading.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Grosvenor Vale
description: It's recommended that supporters travel to Grosvenor Vale via public transport as the club is remarkably well served by tube, train and bus routes.

name: Stainton Park
description: Stainton Park (Neuven Stadium) has been the home of Radcliffe Football Club since 1970. With the help of grants and personal investments, the club have been able to provide 2 Floodlit all weather 3G pitches, a changing room complex, a new sports clinic, an upgrade in the terracing, new car parking space, the purchase of the social club, a new sponsors lounge, a 350-seated stand and six conference standard floodlights. The club hosts local cup finals, charity events and provides facilities for teams such as Rochdale, Accrington Stanley, Bury and Blackburn Rovers Ladies.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Nethermoor Park
description: Nethermoor is made up of covered seated stands, covered terraced stands, and other terraced standing areas. There are turnstiles at three corners of the ground, refreshment blocks, lavatories, a Club Shop, a first aid room, and a spectator first aid room. Kick-off times are usually 3pm on Saturdays and 7.45pm on Tuesdays for midweek matches, and matchday programmes can be purchased for £3 each.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: The Silverlands
description: For visitors to the Tarmac Silverlands Stadium, the club suggests parking in the Market Place Car Park, Sylvan Park, or Spring Gardens Car Park. These car parks are free after 3pm for High Peak residents and after 6pm for everyone else. Advance notice is required for car parking for visitors with access needs.

name: New Meadow Park
description: Limited parking is available on matchdays for blue badge holders and guests. Alternatively, fans can park at Sainsbury's (3 hours free parking), Castlemeads Car Park, or Gloucester Quays Car Park (4 hours for £5). From the North, take the A40 westbound from M5 junction 11 and from the South, take the A38 Quedgeley by-pass from M5 junction 12.

name: York Road
description: Maidenhead United FC play at York Road, a ground which has been their home  since 1871. The ground is situated in the centre of Maidenhead, close to  the town centre and the railway station. Unfortunately, there is no parking  available at York Road Stadium.

name: The Citadel
description: There is a large car park at The Citadel and a limited number of Blue Badge spaces. On match days, we offer a Happy Hour discount in the Nest Bar and there is a fully-stocked club shop selling official Farsley Celtic merchandise, Puma Teamwear and old programmes.

name: North Street
description: Pay and display parking is available on Rogers Lane and also at Severn  Square, both are a 5-10 minute walk from the arena.

name: Giant Axe
description: The grounds have been heavily renovated since the mid-late 1990s and now feature a 513 seat Main Stand, a Club End Terrace and a Shed End covered terrace. Behind the main stand is the main car park and offices and behind the Shed End is a small car park. The old social club, The Dolly Blue Tavern, was vacated in the summer of 2012 and replaced with a new club bar. The club office is located at the rear of the Club End terrace.

name: Turnbull Ground
description: There is limited parking available around the ground, but there is free street parking and pay and display parking at the nearby Leisure Centre. Turnstiles open 1.5 hours prior to kick-off and you can buy merchandise from the club shop. Away supporters should enter through turnstile 4 on Upgang Lane when games are segregated. There is seating available in the main stand and two catering outlets. Make sure to read the ground regulations and safeguarding policy before your visit.

name: Weaver Stadium
description: Visitors can take in the sights of Nantwich Town Centre on the way to the ground, which is an historic market town with the impressive St Mary's Church and Tudor buildings. There are plenty of places to have lunch and drinks.

name: St James Park
description: The car park at St James Park is limited and spaces cost £5 per car. Please note that car park spaces cannot be reserved and are on a  first-come-first-served basis.

name: Horsfall Community Stadium
description: There are refreshment options available such as the Clubhouse bar and the Avenue Café. The Club Shop is located at the Cemetery Road end of the ground and can be used to purchase programmes. There are toilets located around the ground and the club offers accessibility options such as access to the ground via the main gate, free entry for carers/assistants, a designated viewing area for wheelchair users and 2 designated parking spaces for blue badge holders

name: Christchurch Meadow
description: There is limited car parking at the ground, but there are various car parks located in the town. There is free movement throughout the stadium and the club shop is open 60 minutes before kick-off and again at half-time. There are food outlets at the ground and all spectators are welcome in the main function room, where there is also a range of drinks available. Toilets and disabled facilities are available, and dogs are allowed into the stadium.

name: Mount Pleasant
description: Pleasant Stadium is easily accessible by train and car and offers car parking for visitors. Refreshments are available from Neil's Kabin and there is a licensed bar in the clubhouse. A token system is in place for the can bar within the ground. The club shop is open for all home games to purchase Marske United merchandise.

name: Parkfield
description: Exit M25 at Junction 24, take A111 exit (Southgate Road) towards Potters Bar, turn right A1000 onto High Street, turn left into The Walk, turn right into Watkins Rise, ground is to your right. Avoid Mayfair Lodge Car Park.

name: Queen Elizabeth II Stadium
description: An integral part of the Queen Elizabeth II Stadium is the main pavilion, completed in 1953. This is a Grade II listed building built in Art Deco style, and serves as the clubhouse, main stand and changing rooms.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Latimer Park
description: Kettering Town FC moved to their current Latimer Park site in 2013 and hosted their first league game that year. Since then, the ground has grown to accommodate a 500-seat main stand, covered accommodation, and a play-off final in 2014. On April 18, 2015, they won the Southern League Division One Central shield with a 2-1 win over Bedworth United in front of 1,003 spectators.

name: Causeway Lane
description: Matlock Town FC is located 500 yards from the town centre at The Proctor Cars Stadium. On match days, limited parking is available outside the ground on Causeway The ground has a Club Shop, Tea Bar, and Large Social Club with two large screens showing Sky Sports and ESPN games before and after games.

name: Hop Oast Stadium
description: Opened in 2019, the stadium features two top quality 3G playing surfaces built using the latest artificial pitch technology, a covered 300-seater stand, covered standing areas behind each goal and two further covered stands down one side, including seating for 50 spectators.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: The Maurice Rebak Stadium
description: The Wingate and Finchley stadium offers a Fully Licensed bar and food/refreshment hatch 90 minutes prior to kickoff. Bar serves lagers & Guinness, bottled ales, lagers, ciders, spirits, soft drinks and bar snacks. Refreshment hatch serves burgers, hot dogs, chips, soups, hot drinks, soft drinks, crisps, nuts and chocolates. Dogs are welcome. No ATM on site, but there are ATMs in shops, pubs and other entertainment venues nearby. Banks with ATMs can be found on Finchley High Road, about 1 mile from the ground.

memberOf.name: Isthmian League Premier Division
memberOf.alternateName: Pitching In Isthmian League Premier Division

name: Rylands Recreation Club
description: Admission to games is £8 for adults, £5 for concessions, and £2 for U16s and all admission is via the turnstiles. There is a match programme for £2 and refreshments are available before, during and after the match. There is no segregation and home and away flags and banners are welcome.
